column259: I did not like how random it was. I tried to make my investments based on the trends I saw but the trends proved too unpredictable. I did not understand the $20 investment decision...that did not make sense to me why you would take such a risk for so little chance of reward.
The random chosen of path choose my lowest outcome  which dissapoint me.

It was fun.  I became more confident with investing the longer the process went on.  As I began to make bigger risks and found that they didn't pay off  I went back to my original and safer method of investing which I think was the best idea in the first place.  Also  I thought the beginning of the second slew of investments was going to be entirely practice  so I made a lot of risky investments I wouldn't have initially if I had thought it was the real thing.
Today Was A Great Day To Take Actions On Behalf  of The Experience I Made My Decisions Based On The Numbers  From Low To High

Always started with high percentage invested in asset A to get the ball rolling. Changed the percentage I had invested in each asset based on trend in return for asset A. Almost always bought into asset C only when amount of money exceded 5 dollars in order to be sure that my end payout randomly slected would have a small likelihood of being below 3 dollars. No part of expirement not understood.

Kind of frustrating. It took me a long time to find an investment way that I feel mostly comfortable with. |  | I found out that I am more willing to take risks than I thought I was. I regretted some of the decisions I made.

I had a positive experience during the experiment. I normally made my investment decisions based on how much I could allocate to Asset A without my projections dropping below a floor amount I would decide on contingent on the current amount I had in my account. The experiment was clear and very straight forward.

No. I understood all the parts perfectly. | I mostly kept increasing my investment in asset B as my returns increased. Sometimes I made some risky decisions which I now regret. They did pay off at times but when the computer is going to randomly select only 1 of the paths then itsbest to just play safe so that all your paths have almost the same amount.
I just kept in the same general range of about 75% gaurenteed and 25% risk.

Sometimes I made decisions on the previous multiplier that showed up for set A and used a little bit of probability theory as well. Other times  I realized getting a multiplier greater than 1 for A was just pure luck and so I started allocating less and less into set A as B was always sure to pay off positively.
